Pandithamani '''S. Kanapathipillai''' (<U+0BAA><U+0BA3><U+0BCD><U+0B9F><U+0BBF><U+0BA4><U+0BAE><U+0BA3><U+0BBF> <U+0B9A><U+0BBF>. <U+0B95><U+0BA3><U+0BAA><U+0BA4><U+0BBF><U+0BAA><U+0BCD><U+0BAA><U+0BBF><U+0BB3><U+0BCD><U+0BB3><U+0BC8>) (1899-1986) was a minority [[Sri Lankan Tamil]] literary figure and [[Hindu]] [[revivalist]] in the line of [[Arumuga Navalar]]. His father was Sinnathamby Pillai of [[Madduvil]]. Kanapathipillai was enrolled at the Navalar Kaaviya Paadasalai, under Kumaraswamy Pulavar, where he pursued higher studies in [[classical Tamil]] and [[Tamil literature|literature]]. He also came under the guidance of [[Swami Vipulananda]], while still a student at the Navalar Kaaviya Paadasalai.

In 1925, he qualified as [[Pandit|Pandithar]] by the [[Madurai Tamil Sangam]]. There were only four people from [[Jaffna]] who had been bestowed this qualification by the Madurai Sangam at that time. Kanapathipillai was a trained teacher and a [[Sanskrit]] scholar, who was appointed in charge of the Saiva Teachers Training School at [[Thirunelveli]], Jaffna, in 1929. He continued his duties there until he retired. 

He was an authority on [[Saiva Siddhanta]] and is a revered Tamil scholar of high repute. He is respected by many even to date and was honoured with the title of "Pandithamani". His later years were spent at his residence in "Kalasalai Veedi" in Thirunelveli, Jaffna, where he maintained the traditions of Arumuga Navalar.<ref>[http://www.tamilnation.org/hundredtamils/pandithamanikanapathipillai.htm Pandithamani S. Kanapathipillai]</ref><ref>[http://collect.ceylanka.net/default.htm?Bm99160 Government stamp in honor of S. Kanapathipillai]

